{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"454f8c5e-9545-4364-88f5-64f66acd8943","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n### 1. Get into the container\n\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --duration 00:00:30 --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### 5. Copy the trace out of the pod\n\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n---\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available, you can sidecar or pre-install the tool in your container image.\n- For **Windows containers specifically**, `dotnet-trace` (EventPipe-based) is the recommended path — `dotnet-dump` and `perf` aren't applicable on Windows.\n- Use `--profile cpu-sampling` for CPU issues; use `gc-collect` if you suspect GC pressure instead.\n- Convert to `.speedscope` format (`dotnet-trace convert`) for browser-based analysis if you don't have Visual Studio handy.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1819a867-2378-4b76-9926-05260583a4b3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question that doesn't require code changes or file exploration. I can answer this directly from my knowledge.","outputTokens":415,"requestId":"C3DD:27C37:1D772D4:2106539:6A07C140"},"id":"1d28df96-01c3-4dd3-9cdf-a28562c75405","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:58:50.092Z","parentId":"d05988c9-3f7f-4c72-b2a7-70501b09aae6"}
